Even if we had one, which like I said, 99% of the time we don't lol... it's all just a random set of numbers fed into a computer.<br>
<br>
(edit - added the below)<br>
<br>
The difference here is between telemarketers and telephone interviewers... the DNC lists, national or otherwise, are all for telemarketers. By definition, telemarketers are SELLING something... or setting an appointment to SELL something or something of that nature.<br>
<br>
All the telephone interviewers want is to ask you a few questions that are either about something you already own, a business you already use, or political stuff.<br>
<br>
Heres a good way to get off the phone quickly...<br>
<br>
If the interviewer asks &quot;Do you work in X, Y, or Z industries?&quot; tell them yes... 99.9% of the time, that's a &quot;screening&quot; question... and the survey will terminate.<br>
<br>
If they ask in the beginning of the interview for your income... give them the lowest income. 99% of the time that'll terminate the interview (because we don't want to ask people who make 10k a year about services for people who make 100k a year, they wouldn't have a frame of reference)<br>
<br>
If they ask you &quot;do you own such and such&quot; say no.<br>
<br>
If they ask &quot;do you think you will probably vote in the upcoming election for X&quot; say no.<br>
<br>
If they ask if you work in market research, say yes... almost ALL surveys will be terminated by that (not all tho -- political surveys don't do that, and some product surveys don't)<br>
<br>
Alternately of course, you could take the survey... honest, it's not usually very painful. And while there almost always are some &quot;sensitive&quot; questions (income etc) don't get mad at the interviewer for asking them, and then trying to get you to answer them... we tend to lose our jobs if we don't.<br>
<br>
